Example 2: Autoregression

Autoregression is a time series model that uses observations from previous time steps as input to a regression equation to predict the value at the next time step.

It is a very simple idea that can result in accurate forecasts on a range of time series problems.

Suppose we consider the white noise series \(w_t\) (above mentioned) as input and calculate the output using the second-order equation

\[x_t = x_{t-1}-0.9x_{t-2}+w_t\]

successively for \(t = 1,2,...,500\). Above equation represents a regression or prediction of the current value \(x_t\) of a time series as a function of the past two values of the series, and, hence, the term autoregression is suggested for this model.

One way to simulate and plot data from the model in R is to use the following commands (another way is to use arima.sim).

w = rnorm(550,0,1) # 50 extra to avoid startup problems
x = filter(w, filter=c(1,-.9), method="recursive")[-(1:50)] 
#If "convolution" a moving average is used: 
#and if "recursive" an autoregression is used.#
plot.ts(x, main="autoregression")

or we can use arima.sim:

w2 = arima.sim(model = list(order=c(2,0,0), ar=c(1,-0.9)) , n=500)
plot(w2)

or

AR2 <- arima.sim(n = 500, model = list(ar = c(0.9, -0.6)), sd = 1)

Moving Average Smoothing

(Centered Moving Average) We might replace the white noise series \(w_t\) by a moving average that smooths the series. For example, consider replacing the white noise mentioned above, \(w_t\) by an average of its current value and its immediate neighbors in the past and future. That is, let

\(v_t= \frac{1}{3}(w_{t-1} + w_t + w_{t+1} )\)

A linear combination of values in a time series such as in above formula, is referred to, generically, as a filtered series; hence the command filter has been used.

w = rnorm(500,0,1) # 500 N(0,1) variates 
v = filter(w, sides=2, filter=rep(1/3,3)) # moving average 
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot.ts(w, main="white noise")
plot.ts(v, ylim=c(-3,3), main="moving average")

Inspecting the series shows a smoother version of the first series, reflecting the fact that the slower oscillations are more apparent and some of the faster oscillations are taken out.

Example: Residential electricity sales (excluding hot water) for South Australia: 1989–2008.

autoplot(elecsales) + xlab("Year") + ylab("GWh") +
  ggtitle("Annual electricity sales: South Australia")

ma(elecsales, 5) #calculate 5-MA

5-MA

autoplot(elecsales, series="Data") +
  autolayer(ma(elecsales,5), series="5-MA") +
  xlab("Year") + ylab("GWh") +
  ggtitle("Annual electricity sales: South Australia") +
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("Data"="grey50","5-MA"="red"),
                      breaks=c("Data","5-MA"))
## Warning: Removed 4 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

Notice that the trend-cycle (in red) is smoother than the original data and captures the main movement of the time series without all of the minor fluctuations. The order of the moving average determines the smoothness of the trend-cycle estimate. In general, a larger order means a smoother curve.

The effect of changing the order of the moving average for the residential electricity sales data.

Simple moving averages such as these are usually of an odd order (e.g., 3, 5, 7, etc.). This is so they are symmetric: in a moving average of order m=2k+1, the middle observation, and k observations on either side, are averaged. But if m was even, it would no longer be symmetric.

Moving averages of moving averages (even-order moving window)

It is possible to apply a moving average to a moving average. One reason for doing this is to make an even-order moving average symmetric.

For example, we might take a moving average of order 4, and then apply another moving average of order 2 to the results. In the following table, this has been done for the first few years of the Australian quarterly beer production data.

beer2 <- window(ausbeer,start=1992)
ma4 <- ma(beer2, order=4, centre=FALSE)
ma2x4 <- ma(beer2, order=4, centre=TRUE)
MA=data.frame()

The notation “ 2×4-MA” in the last column means a 4-MA followed by a 2-MA. The values in the last column are obtained by taking a moving average of order 2 of the values in the previous column.

For example, the first two values in the 4-MA column are 451.25=(443+410+420+532)/4 and 448.75=(410+420+532+433)/4. The first value in the 2x4-MA column is the average of these two: 450.00=(451.25+448.75)/2.

Example: Electrical equipment manufacturing

autoplot(elecequip, series="Data") +
  autolayer(ma(elecequip, 12, centre=TRUE), series="12-MA") +
  xlab("Year") + ylab("New orders index") +
  ggtitle("Electrical equipment manufacturing (Euro area)") +
  scale_colour_manual(values=c("Data"="grey","12-MA"="red"),
                      breaks=c("Data","12-MA"))
## Warning: Removed 12 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

A 2x12-MA applied to the electrical equipment orders index.

Notice that the smooth line shows no seasonality; Any other choice for the order of the moving average (except for 24, 36, etc.) would have resulted in a smooth line that showed some seasonal fluctuations.

  1. Smoothing Moving Average

(a). Simulate a 5 point moving average using filter(),

the formula is:

\(v_t= \frac{1}{5}(w_{t-2}+w_{t-1} + w_t + w_{t+1}+w_{t+2})\)

where t is the time step that you are smoothing at and 5 is the number of points being used to calculate the average.

a = rnorm(600,0,1) 
b = filter(a, sides=2, filter=rep(1/5,5))
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot.ts(a, main="white noise")
plot.ts(b, ylim=c(-5,5), main="moving average of 5")

  1. AR(p) model

(a). Simulate and plot an AR(2) with parameters 1.5 and -.75 with sample size 200 using arima.sim(). Also, write down the formula for this process.

ar2_model = arima.sim(model = list(order=c(2,0,0), ar=c(1.5,-0.75)) , n=200)
plot(ar2_model)

#Formula: Zt = φ1Zt-1 + φ2Zt-2 + at
#where  φ1 = -0.75, φ2 = 1.5

(b). Generate PACF plot and discuss what can you observe from the plot.

pacf(arima.sim(model = list(order=c(2,0,0), ar=c(1.5,-0.75)) , n=200), ylab="x",
main=("PACF plot with phi = 1.5 and -0.75"))

#The observation from the plot is that it is stationary after lag = 2 therefore it is independent of time
  1. MA(q) Model

#The autocorrelation plot shows that the time series is stationary and independent of time
  1. Simulations to get an idea of what actual ACF and PACF plots may appear like for AR(p) Vs. MA(q) models:

(a). Simulate MA(2) process with coefficents 0.9 and 0.6 for a sample size 100.Plot the ACF and PACF and Comment/discuss.

ma2_model = arima.sim(model = list(order=c(0,0,2), ma=c(0.9,0.6)) , n=100)
plot(ma2_model)

acf(arima.sim(model = list(order=c(0,0,2), ma=c(0.9,0.6)) , n=100), ylab="x",
main=("ACF plot with phi = 0.9 and 0.6"))

pacf(arima.sim(model = list(order=c(0,0,2), ma=c(0.9,0.6)) , n=100), ylab="x",
main=("PACF plot with phi = 0.9 and 0.6"))

#The acf plot is stationary which means that there is no correlation of the time series observations with values of the same series, but at previous times whereas the pacf plot is not stationary till lag =5 which makes the relationship between an observation in a time series with observations at previous time steps, but with the relationships of intervening observations removed significant.
#As there is a downtailing, we can say that it indicates an underlying ARMA model

(b). Simulate AR(2) process with coefficents 0.9 and -0.6 for a sample size 100. Plot the ACF and PACF and Comment/discuss.

ar2_model1 = arima.sim(model = list(order=c(2,0,0), ar=c(0.9,-0.6)) , n=100)
plot(ar2_model1)

acf(arima.sim(model = list(order=c(2,0,0), ar=c(0.9,-0.6)) , n=100), ylab="x",
main=("ACF plot with phi = 0.9 and 0.6"))

pacf(arima.sim(model = list(order=c(2,0,0), ar=c(0.9,-0.6)) , n=100), ylab="x",
main=("PACF plot with phi = 0.9 and 0.6"))

#In the AR(2) model, we observe the opposite nature than that to the plots above where acp plot is non stationary till lag 3 and stationary for pacf plot.
#There is also a downtailing which proves that there is an underlying ARMA model

(Hint: It is clear that when you examine the MA(2) through an ACF and an AR(2) through a PACF that the cutoff happens after lag 2 for each of those corresponding plots. In the other plots however you see a slow ‘tailing-off’ which is typical. If you encounter a rough where the ACF and PACF both are tailing off, it indicates that there is an underlying \(ARMA(p,q)\) model.)
